# Setup checklist — {{PROJECT_NAME}}

This file is the source of truth for whether this project's guardrails are actually in place. The agent re-reads this file rather than relying on conversation memory — especially after a long session, or at the start of any new session, if there's any doubt. Every box must be checked before feature work begins in earnest. For a retrofit of an existing project, this file instead reflects what's currently missing and doubles as the to-do list to close the gap.

## 0. Stack maturity — what applies now, what's deferred

Not every project has every piece of the stack from day one — a project that's "barely getting started" may genuinely have no database, no typed language, no test framework, and no UI yet. That's a legitimate state, not a gap to force-fill during setup. For each optional piece below, mark its actual status:

- Database / backend with persistence: [ ] Not applicable   [ ] Deferred   [ ] Active — which: ___
- Per-user or per-role access control (RLS or equivalent): [ ] Not applicable   [ ] Deferred   [ ] Active
- Typed language / strict typing mechanism: [ ] Not applicable   [ ] Deferred   [ ] Active — which: ___
- Automated test framework: [ ] Not applicable   [ ] Deferred   [ ] Active — which: ___
- UI: [ ] Not applicable   [ ] Deferred   [ ] Active
- AI-native (model-call) feature: [ ] Not applicable   [ ] Deferred   [ ] Active

**Not applicable requires the project owner's explicit confirmation that this project will never need the piece — never mark it on inferred judgment alone.** "Deferred" is the default for anything genuinely not built yet, and it's not the same as "missing" — a box under a Deferred section stays unchecked without that being a problem to fix today.

**The trigger, for anything marked Deferred:** the first commit that actually introduces that piece — the first migration, the first typed file, the first test file, the first table with an owner column, the first UI component — is itself a setup event, not just a feature commit. Before that commit lands: flip the status above from Deferred to Active, then satisfy the relevant section below *first*, not retrofitted after the fact once code depending on it already exists. This is `setup` run in miniature, scoped to just that one piece — see `CLAUDE.md` rule 11.

## 1. Law and rules
- [ ] `CLAUDE.md` generated and present at repo root
- [ ] Plan-first rule confirmed in `CLAUDE.md`
- [ ] Architectural pattern stated (what it is: ___)
- [ ] `.ae-kit-version` present at repo root and matches `ae-setup/kit/VERSION` (see `CLAUDE.md` rule 12) — confirms this project's skills/templates aren't running a stale copy of the kit

## 2. Git discipline
- [ ] Branch policy confirmed and recorded in `CLAUDE.md` → Git conventions (branch-per-task, or this project's actual direct-to-main convention — which: ___)
- [ ] Commit message format confirmed and recorded in `CLAUDE.md` → Git conventions (WHAT/WHY/RISK, or this project's actual existing convention — which: ___)
- [ ] `index.lock` handling procedure present in the `commit` skill

## 3. Structure locks
- [ ] {{STRICT_TYPING_MECHANISM}} enabled and verified (e.g. `tsconfig.json` has `"strict": true`, or `mypy`/Pydantic configured) — if section 0 marks typed language as Deferred, this box stays unchecked until that trigger fires; it does not apply to a project with no code yet
- [ ] Lint configured and passing on a clean checkout
- [ ] `verify-rls` skill present and reflects this project's actual role model, if this project has per-user or per-role data access ({{RLS_OR_EQUIVALENT}}) — see section 0's access-control status; Not applicable or Deferred both leave this unchecked legitimately

## 3b. Schema versioning (Supabase projects — prerequisite for section 4, applies once section 0 marks the database as Active)
- [ ] `supabase/migrations/` folder and `config.toml` exist
- [ ] Migrations reflect the actual current production schema — **(retrofit only)** if schema was ever built ad hoc (changes applied directly via dashboard/SQL editor, never captured in git — check by comparing the count of applied migrations in the Supabase dashboard against what's in `supabase/migrations/` locally), baseline it now: `supabase init` → `supabase link --project-ref <ref>` → `supabase db pull`. The individual history of prior ad hoc changes is not recoverable — the pulled baseline becomes the new starting point, and that's an acceptable one-time cost.
- [ ] Confirmed going forward every schema change is a migration file (`supabase migration new <name>`), never SQL run directly against any database by hand
- [ ] **Do not check any box in section 4 (Sandbox) until this section is fully checked** — a reproducible sandbox requires reproducible migrations; without this, "sandbox" setup degrades into manually eyeballing two databases, which is the fragile process this framework exists to avoid

