## 4b. Secrets hygiene
- [ ] `.env.example` copied in, real values filled into `.env.local` (the actual convention this stack's tooling auto-loads and treats as git-ignorable — never invent a name like `.env.dev`), never into `.env.example` itself, and never into a bare `.env` either
- [ ] `.env*` (except `.env.example`) confirmed present in `.gitignore` — explicitly check both `.env` and `.env.local` are listed, not just one
- [ ] Confirmed no API key, password, or connection string exists in `CLAUDE.md`, `SETUP_CHECKLIST.md`, `TASKS.md`, or any file under `.claude/skills/`
- [ ] **(retrofit only, mandatory before anything else in this section counts as done)** Ran a real content-scanning tool across the full git history — `gitleaks git .` (not just a filename grep like `git log -- .env` — a real leak was found once already sitting in a plain `docs/*.md` file, which a filename-based check would never catch, since secrets can hide in *any* tracked file: docs, READMEs, comments, seed scripts, not just conventional env/key files). **If `gitleaks` itself can't be installed in the current execution environment** (e.g. a cloud agent sandbox with restricted network access to GitHub/the Go proxy — confirmed to happen), an equivalent full-content scanner across the same full history (`detect-secrets` plus a manual regex sweep of the complete diff, for example) satisfies this requirement equally — the bar is a real content scan across every commit, not the specific binary. **If anything turns up: the credential must be rotated or disabled at its source immediately.** Untracking the file or editing it out afterward is cleanup, not remediation — it does not undo the exposure. A warning comment written next to a secret ("don't commit this") is not a safeguard and does not count as mitigation. Do not check this box until rotation/disabling is confirmed done, not just scheduled.
- [ ] `gitleaks` (or equivalent) installed as a pre-commit hook (via Husky or the `pre-commit` framework — `gitleaks protect --staged` on every commit) so a secret is blocked *before* it lands on a branch, not caught later in a periodic scan. This is the first structural fix; the scan above is the one-time catch-up for history that already exists.
- [ ] `gitleaks-workflow.yml.template` copied to `.github/workflows/gitleaks.yml` — the CI backstop that catches anything the local hook misses (unhooked clone, `--no-verify`, a direct push), visible as a pass/fail check on every PR. Runs on GitHub's own runners, so it's unaffected by any network restriction in whatever environment ran the one-time history scan above. Not a replacement for the pre-commit hook above; both matter, since either one alone can be bypassed.

## 5. Verification
- [ ] At least one deterministic test exists and passes — if section 0 marks the test framework as Deferred (no code to test yet), this stays unchecked legitimately; it becomes due the moment the first test-worthy code is written, per the section 0 trigger
- [ ] Eval harness present, if this project has any AI-native (model-call) feature: ___ — see section 0's AI-native status
- [ ] UI walkthrough step confirmed in `verify-ui`, if this project has a UI — see section 0's UI status

## 6. Task tracking
- [ ] `TASKS.md` exists and is empty or seeded with current `in progress`/`in review` work
- [ ] `BACKLOG.md` exists (holds not-yet-started ideas as one-liners, no size cap)
- [ ] `TASKS_ARCHIVE.md` exists (can start empty)
- [ ] `TASKS_ARCHIVE_INDEX.md` exists (can start empty — only gets a row once `TASKS_ARCHIVE.md` first reaches its 50-entry split, at which point the split file lives under a `tasks-archive/` subfolder, not the project root)
- [ ] `/logs/` directory exists
- [ ] `STATUS.md` exists with a `maturity:` field set

## 7. Maturity
- [ ] `maturity:` field set in `STATUS.md` (prototype / pre-users / live-users)
- [ ] Confirmed this reflects the project's actual real-world status, not a default

## 8. Cowork native loading (skip if this project is only ever worked on via Claude Code)
- [ ] `COWORK_PROJECT_INSTRUCTIONS.md` generated
- [ ] Its content pasted into this project's Cowork Settings → Project Instructions — a manual step, not something the agent can do itself

---

**When every box above is checked (or legitimately unchecked as Not applicable / Deferred per section 0), setup is done.** Modifying project specifics after this point (adding a new table, a new skill, changing the stack) does not require re-running the full setup interview — just update the relevant section of this checklist and the affected files directly. Flipping a section 0 status from Deferred to Active does require satisfying that piece's section before the triggering commit lands (see section 0 and `CLAUDE.md` rule 11).

## Supabase free-tier sandbox — reference block

Use this exact block in section 4 for any Supabase project on the free tier (branching requires a paid plan):

```
- [ ] Sandbox: second Supabase project created (name: ___, URL/keys in .env.local)
- [ ] Sandbox: dev project seeded with fake data
- [ ] Sandbox: reset script written and tested (path: ___)
- [ ] Sandbox: prod credentials confirmed absent from dev environment entirely
```
